XIoKWA8YnI+IDUuIHByb2Nlc3MgdGhlIHRlbXBsYXRlczogYHIucnVuKClg\r\nPGJyPiA8YnI+IFRlbXBsYXRlUnVubmVyIHRha2VzIGNhcmUgb2YgY29uZmlndXJpbmcgYmFzaWMg\r\nRGphbmdvIHNldHRpbmdzIGZvciB5b3UsIHByb2Nlc3NlcyB0aGUgdGVtcGxhdGVzIHdpdGggdGhl\r\nIGNvbnRleHRzLCBhbmQgc2F2ZXMgdGhlIG91dHB1dCBmaWxlcyAoLmh0bWwpIGFsb25nc2lkZSB0\r\naGUgdGVtcGxhdGVzOjxicj4gPGJyPiBgYGA8YnI+IG15X3Byb2plY3QvPGJyPiDilJTilIDilIAg\r\ndGVtcGxhdGVfcnVubmVyPGJyPiAmbmJzcDsmbmJzcDsmbmJzcDsg4pSc4pSA4pSAIGNvbnRleHRz\r\nLnB5PGJyPiAmbmJzcDsmbmJzcDsmbmJzcDsg4pSc4pSA4pSAIHRlbXBsYXRlX3J1bm5lci5weTxi\r\ncj4gJm5ic3A7Jm5ic3A7Jm5ic3A7IOKUlOKUgOKUgCB0ZW1wbGF0ZXM8YnI+ICZuYnNwOyZuYnNw\r\nOyZuYnNwOyZuYnNwOyZuYnNwOyDilJzilIDilIAgYmFzZV90ZW1wbGF0ZV9leGFtcGxlLmRqLmh0\r\nbWw8YnI+ICZuYnNwOyZuYnNwOyZuYnNwOyZuYnNwOyZuYnNwOyDilJzilIDilIAgaW5kZXguZGou\r\naHRtbDxicj4gJm5ic3A7Jm5ic3A7Jm5ic3A7Jm5ic3A7Jm5ic3A7IOKUlOKUgOKUgCBpbmRleC5o\r\ndG1sPGJyPiBgYGA8YnI+IDxicj4gT25jZSB5b3Ugc2V0IHRoaW5ncyB1cCB5b3UgY2FuIGFjaGll\r\ndmUgYSBwcmV0dHkgZmFzdCB3b3JrZmxvdy4gSSB1c2UgU3VibGltZSBUZXh0IDIgd2l0aCB0aGUg\r\nU3VibGltZVJFUEwgcGFja2FnZSwgc28gSSBkb24ndCBldmVuIGhhdmUgdG8gbGVhdmUgdGhlIGVk\r\naXRvciB0byBydW4gbXkgdGVtcGxhdGVzLiBJIGp1c3QgbWFkZSB0aGlzIGZvciBteSBvd24gcGVy\r\nc29uYWwgdXNlLCBidXQgaWYgeW91IGZpbmQgaXQgdXNlZnVsIHlvdSBjYW4gZmluZCB0aGUgc291\r\ncmNlIGNvZGUgb24gW0dpdEh1Yl0oaHR0cHM6Ly9naXRodWIuY29tL2pzb25icmF6ZWFsL2RqYW5n\r\nby10ZW1wbGF0ZS1ydW5uZXIpLjxicj4gPGJyPiBXaGF0J3MgeW91ciBwcmVmZXJyZWQgd2F5IHRv\r\nIGdvIGFib3V0IHRlbXBsYXRpbmcgd2hlbiBidWlsZGluZyBhIHNtYWxsLCBtb3N0bHkgc3RhdGlj\r\nIHNpdGU/Jm5ic3A7PGJyPjwvZGl2Pg==\">​</div>\r\n</div>','Django TemplateRunner','','inherit','open','open','','15-revision-v1','','','2014-05-23 13:04:47','2014-05-23 17:04:47','',15,'http://localhost:8008/blog/15-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(21,1,'2014-05-23 12:59:14','2014-05-23 16:59:14','<div class=\"markdown-here-wrapper\" data-md-url=\"http://localhost:8008/blog/wp-admin/post.php?post=15&amp;action=edit\">\r\n<p style=\"margin: 1.2em 0px !important;\">I love working with Django, but you don’t need the entire framework for every web project. If I’m making a small, mostly static site, I like to start with a base index.html and CSS files from <a href=\"http://html5boilerplate.com/\">html5bp</a> or <a href=\"http://getbootstrap.com/\">bootstrap</a>. Without using a templating system, the second page I made would violate one of <a href=\"https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/dev/misc/design-philosophies/\">Django’s design philosophies</a> and a well-accepted good programming practice: DRY - Don’t Repeat Yourself. I know it might be easier to use PHP and that there are even standalone Python templating engines that can do this and more (see <a href=\"http://jinja.pocoo.org/\">Jinja</a>), but I wanted to try my hand at building a class that used Django’s machinery and allowed me to write Django templates and process them using context variables. So I came up with TemplateRunner.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 1.2em 0px !important;\">TemplateRunner can be run from the command line anywhere on your machine, but it does make a few assumptions. The template_runner.py module has to be in a location on your Python path, and that location must also contain a contexts.py module a templates folder with the templates (ending in .dj.html):</p>\r\n\r\n<pre style=\"font-size: 1.2em; font-family: Consolas, Inconsolata, Courier, monospace; line-height: 1em; padding: 0px; margin: 1.2em 0px;\"><code style=\"font-size: 0.85em; font-family: Consolas, Inconsolata, Courier, monospace; margin: 0px 0.15em; padding: 0.5em; white-space: pre; border-top-left-radius: 3px; border-top-right-radius: 3px; border-bottom-right-radius: 3px; border-bottom-left-radius: 3px; display: block; background-color: #f8f8f8; overflow: auto; color: #cccccc; background: #2d2d2d;\"> my_project/\r\n └── template_runner\r\n ├── contexts.py\r\n ├── template_runner.py\r\n └── templates\r\n ├── base_template_example.dj.html\r\n └── index.dj.html\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 1.2em 0px !important;\">The contexts module should contain a single constant CONTEXTS which is a dictionary whose keys are the templates and whose values are the context dictionaries for those templates, for example:</p>\r\n\r\n<pre style=\"font-size: 1.2em; font-family: Consolas, Inconsolata, Courier, monospace; line-height: 1em; padding: 0px; margin: 1.2em 0px;\"><code class=\"language-python\" style=\"font-size: 0.85em; font-family: Consolas, Inconsolata, Courier, monospace; margin: 0px 0.15em; padding: 0.5em; white-space: pre; border-top-left-radius: 3px; border-top-right-radius: 3px; border-bottom-right-radius: 3px; border-bottom-left-radius: 3px; display: block; background-color: #f8f8f8; overflow: auto; color: #cccccc; background: #2d2d2d;\"> CONTEXTS = {\r\n\r\n<span class=\"string\" style=\"color: #99cc99;\">\'index.dj.html\'</span>: {\r\n <span class=\"string\" style=\"color: #99cc99;\">\'page_title\'</span>: <span class=\"string\" style=\"color: #99cc99;\">\'Welcome to my Blog!\'</span>,\r\n <span class=\"string\" style=\"color: #99cc99;\">\'page_description\'</span>: <span class=\"string\" style=\"color: #99cc99;\">\'blog landing page\'</span>,\r\n },\r\n <span class=\"string\" style=\"color: #99cc99;\">\'contact.dj.html\'</span>: {\r\n <span class=\"string\" style=\"color: #99cc99;\">\'page_title\'</span>: <span class=\"string\" style=\"color: #99cc99;\">\'Contact Me\'</span>,\r\n <span class=\"string\" style=\"color: #99cc99;\">\'page_description\'</span>: <span class=\"string\" style=\"color: #99cc99;\">\'contact form\'</span>,\r\n }\r\n\r\n}\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 1.2em 0px !important;\">One way to use this class is:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol style=\"margin: 1.2em 0px; padding-left: 2em;\">\r\n<ol style=\"margin: 1.2em 0px; padding-left: 2em;\">\r\n	<li style=\"margin: 0.5em 0px;\">set up your directory structure as described above\r\n<ol style=\"margin: 0px; padding-left: 1em;\">\r\n<ol style=\"margin: 0px; padding-left: 1em;\">\r\n	<li style=\"margin: 0.5em 0px;\">make sure the template_runner directory is on your Python path</li>\r\n	<li style=\"margin: 0.5em 0px;\">import the class:\r\n<pre style=\"display: inline; width: 15%; font-size: 1.2em; font-family: Consolas, Inconsolata, Courier, monospace; line-height: 1em; padding: 0px; margin: 1.2em 0px;\"><code class=\"language-python\" style=\"font-size: 0.85em; font-family: Consolas, Inconsolata, Courier, monospace; margin: 0px 0.15em; padding: 0.5em; white-space: pre; border-top-left-radius: 3px; border-top-right-radius: 3px; border-bottom-right-radius: 3px; border-bottom-left-radius: 3px; display: block; background-color: #f8f8f8; overflow: auto; color: #cccccc; background: #2d2d2d;\"><span class=\"keyword\" style=\"color: #cc99cc;\">from</span> template_runner <span class=\"keyword\" style=\"color: #cc99cc;\">import</span> TemplateRunner</code></pre>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li style=\"margin: 0.5em 0px;\">instantiate a TemplateRunner object:\r\n<pre style=\"font-size: 1.2em; font-family: Consolas, Inconsolata, Courier, monospace; line-height: 1em; padding: 0px; margin: 1.2em 0px;\"><code class=\"language-python\" style=\"font-size: 0.85em; font-family: Consolas, Inconsolata, Courier, monospace; margin: 0px 0.15em; padding: 0.5em; white-space: pre; border-top-left-radius: 3px; border-top-right-radius: 3px; border-bottom-right-radius: 3px; border-bottom-left-radius: 3px; display: block; background-color: #f8f8f8; overflow: auto; color: #cccccc; background: #2d2d2d;\">r = TemplateRunner()</code></pre>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li style=\"margin: 0.5em 0px;\">process the templates:\r\n<pre style=\"font-size: 1.2em; font-family: Consolas, Inconsolata, Courier, monospace; line-height: 1em; padding: 0px; margin: 1.2em 0px;\"><code class=\"language-python\" style=\"font-size: 0.85em; font-family: Consolas, Inconsolata, Courier, monospace; margin: 0px 0.15em; padding: 0.5em; white-space: pre; border-top-left-radius: 3px; border-top-right-radius: 3px; border-bottom-right-radius: 3px; border-bottom-left-radius: 3px; display: block; background-color: #f8f8f8; overflow: auto; color: #cccccc; background: #2d2d2d;\">r.run()\r\n</code></pre>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p style=\"margin: 1.2em 0px !important;\">TemplateRunner takes care of configuring basic Django settings for you, processes the templates with the contexts, and saves the output files (.html) alongside the templates:</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<pre style=\"font-size: 1.2em; font-family: Consolas, Inconsolata, Courier, monospace; line-height: 1em; padding: 0px; margin: 1.2em 0px;\"><code style=\"font-size: 0.85em; font-family: Consolas, Inconsolata, Courier, monospace; margin: 0px 0.15em; padding: 0.5em; white-space: pre; border-top-left-radius: 3px; border-top-right-radius: 3px; border-bottom-right-radius: 3px; border-bottom-left-radius: 3px; display: block; background-color: #f8f8f8; overflow: auto; color: #cccccc; background: #2d2d2d;\"> my_project/\r\n └── template_runner\r\n ├── contexts.py\r\n ├── template_runner.py\r\n └── templates\r\n ├── base_template_example.dj.html\r\n ├── index.dj.html\r\n └── index.html\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 1.2em 0px !important;\">Once you set things up you can achieve a pretty fast workflow. I use Sublime Text 2 with the SublimeREPL package, so I don’t even have to leave the editor to run my templates. I just made this for my own personal use, but if you find it useful you can find the source code on <a href=\"https://github.com/jsonbrazeal/django-template-runner\">GitHub</a>.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 1.2em 0px !important;\">What’s your preferred way to go about templating when building a small, mostly static site?</p>\r\n\r\n<div style=\"height: 0; font-size: 0em; padding: 0; margin: 0;\" title=\"MDH:PHA+SSBsb3ZlIHdvcmtpbmcgd2l0aCBEamFuZ28sIGJ1dCB5b3UgZG9uJ3QgbmVlZCB0aGUgZW50 aXJlIGZyYW1ld29yayBmb3IgZXZlcnkgd2ViIHByb2plY3QuIElmIEknbSBtYWtpbmcgYSBzbWFs bCwgbW9zdGx5IHN0YXRpYyBzaXRlLCBJIGxpa2UgdG8gc3Rh